  "prompt": "What is the difference between high fidelity and actual design?",
  "response": "Here's a comparison between high-fidelity and actual design:\n\nHigh Fidelity Design:\n- Detailed visual representation\n- Close to final product appearance\n- Uses precise colors, typography, and graphics\n- Interactive and clickable prototype\n- Demonstrates design aesthetics\n- Used for user testing and stakeholder presentations\n- Requires significant design effort\n- Typically created in design tools like Figma or Sketch\n\nActual Design:\n- Final implementation of design\n- Developed by developers\n- Includes technical specifications\n- Functional and operational\n- Considers technical constraints\n- Integrates with actual code and systems\n- Requires collaboration between designers and developers\n- Involves real-world technical considerations\n\nKey Differences:\n1. Purpose\n- High Fidelity: Visualization and testing\n- Actual Design: Functional implementation\n\n2. Creation Process\n- High Fidelity: Design tools\n- Actual Design: Programming and development environments\n\n3. Level of Detail\n- High Fidelity: Visual representation\n- Actual Design: Technical implementation\n\n4. Interactivity\n- High Fidelity: Simulated interactions\n- Actual Design: Real system interactions\n\nBoth are crucial stages in creating a comprehensive, user-friendly digital product.",
